1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 a6 8.
O-O-O Bd7 9. f4 b5 10. Bxf6 gxf6 11. Kb1 Qb6 12. Nxc6 Bxc6 13. f5 Qc5 $5 (13...
b4 14. Ne2 e5 15. Ng3 h5 {is our main line but 13...Qc5 is also interesting.})
14. Bd3 h5 {Typical idea, Black is preparing for ...Bh6.} 15. Qe1 b4 $1 16. Ne2
{White is now threatening to play first 17.fxe6 and then 18.Nf4.} (16. Nd5 Bxd5
17. exd5 e5 $132 {[%cal Ge8e7,Gf8h6,Ga6a5,Ga5a4,Ga4a3] You can find
information about these types of positions at Structure 6. Examining Edouard,
Romain-Jankovic,Alojzije 2012 game will also help you to understand this pawn
structure.}) 16... e5 $1 {It is very important to close the centre wih this
typical move when the knight comes to e2.} 17. h4 {[%cal Ge2g3] White is
targeting to win the h5-pawn via Ng3 in the future by fixing it. However,
there is not enough time for it.} (17. Ng3 $2 h4 18. Nf1 Ke7 $17 {[%cal Gf8h6,
Ga6a5,Ga5a4] White has a very passive position and all Black pieces are
ideally located. Black is clearly better.}) (17. Qh4 $6 {[%csl Rf6]} Ke7 $1 18.
Nc1 {[%cal Gc1b3]} (18. Ng3 Bh6 $1 {A very typical sacrifice, Black gives up
the h-pawn but in return gains a serious initiative.} 19. Qxh5 (19. Nxh5 $2 Bg5
20. Qg4 a5 21. Ng3 a4 {[%cal Ga4a3]} 22. Ne2 b3 $19 {Black has a crushing
attack.}) 19... a5 20. Qe2 a4 21. Bc4 Bg5 $17 {[%cal Gh8h4] Black has a big
advantage.}) 18... a5 19. Nb3 Qe3 20. Rhe1 Qb6 21. Bc4 a4 22. Nc1 Bh6 $1 23.
Qxh5 $6 {[%csl Rf7]} Raf8 {[%csl Rh2]} 24. Qf3 Bxc1 25. Kxc1 Rxh2 $17 {[%cal
Gb6c5,Gf8g8] Black is clearly better.}) (17. c3 a5 18. cxb4 axb4 19. Nc1 Bh6
20. Bc2 Rg8 21. g3 Bxc1 $1 22. Rxc1 Qd4 $15 {[%cal Gb4b3,Gg8g4] It is
difficult to play this position with White pieces because of the weakness of
the e4-pawn and the open a-file.}) (17. Nc1 {[%cal Gc1b3]} a5 {[%cal Ga5a4]}
18. Nb3 Qb6 19. Bc4 a4 20. Nc1 a3 21. b3 Ke7 22. Qe2 h4 $132 {[%cal Gf8h6]
Black has a very strong counterplay.}) 17... Bh6 18. Rh3 (18. Nc1 a5 19. Nb3
Qb6 20. Nd2 Ke7 21. Nc4 Qc5 $17 {[%cal Ga5a4,Ga4a3,Gh8g8] Black has taken the
whole board under his control.}) (18. Ng3 Bf4 19. Ne2 Be3 20. Nc1 a5 21. Nb3
Qb6 22. Bc4 (22. Nd2 {[%cal Gd2c4]} Bxd2 $5 23. Qxd2 Ke7 $17 {[%cal Gh8g8,
Gb6c5] Black will improve his position with ...Qc5, ...Rhg8. Black is clearly
better.}) 22... Ke7 23. Rh3 Bf2 24. Qe2 a4 25. Nc1 Rac8 26. Rhd3 Bd4 $17 {
[%csl Gd4] Black has managed to transfer his bishop on h6 to d4. This is a
dream position for Black.}) 18... Ke7 {The e7-square is perfect for Black's
king.} 19. Ng3 Rag8 $1 {[%cal Gh6f4] Black wants to play ...Bf4.} 20. Qf1 (20.
Bxa6 Bf4 21. Ne2 Rxg2 $19 {Black's position is winning.}) 20... Bf4 21. Qf3 (
21. Ne2 Rg4 $19 {[%cal Gh8g8] Black is ready to play ...Rhg8. Black has a
winning advantage.}) 21... Qe3 (21... Bxg3 $1 {I guess Jankovic did not want
to give up the bishop pair but rather than playing endgame, it would be more
effective to exchange the bishop with the knight and resume the attack.} 22.
Rxg3 a5 {[%cal Ga4a3,Ga5a4]} 23. b3 (23. Rxg8 Rxg8 24. Qxh5 Rxg2 25. Qf3 Qf2
26. Qxf2 Rxf2 {[%cal Gf2h2]} 27. Rh1 d5 $19 {This endgame is winning for Black.
}) 23... Rxg3 24. Qxg3 a4 $19 {[%cal Ga4a3] This position is hopeless for
White.}) 22. Qxe3 (22. Ne2 Qxf3 23. gxf3 a5 24. Nxf4 exf4 $17 {[%cal Gg8g2]
Black controls the g-file and he has a big advantage.}) 22... Bxe3 23. Be2 (23.
Nxh5 $2 Bf2 {[%csl Rh5]} 24. Be2 Bxe4 25. g4 d5 $19) (23. Bxa6 $2 Bf4 24. Ne2
Rxg2 25. Nxf4 exf4 $19) 23... Bf2 24. Nh1 Rxg2 $1 {A very impressive exchange
sacrifice. Due to the lack of coordination between White pieces and the
weakness of the pawns, it looks very difficult to defend this position for
White.} 25. Bf3 Rhg8 26. Bxg2 Rxg2 27. Nxf2 (27. Rf1 $6 {is dubious and after}
Bc5 28. Ng3 a5 $19 {[%csl Gc5,Gc6] Black has a winning advantage.}) 27... Rxf2
28. Re3 Rh2 {[%csl Rh4] Black wins the second pawn.} 29. Rde1 (29. a3 Rxh4 30.
Rde1 (30. axb4 Bxe4 $19 {[%csl Rf5] White loses all of his central pawns.})
30... bxa3 31. b3 (31. Rxa3 $2 Bxe4 32. Rxa6 Bxf5 $19) 31... Rg4 32. Ka2 h4 33.
c4 (33. Kxa3 h3 $1 34. Rxh3 Bxe4 $19 {[%csl Rf5]}) 33... h3 34. Rxh3 Bxe4 35.
Rh5 Rf4 $17 {[%csl Rf5] It does not seem very easy to defend against all of
the Black central pawns.}) 29... Rxh4 30. a3 bxa3 31. b3 (31. bxa3 Rf4 $17 {
[%cal Gh5h4,Gh4h3] Black will play ...h4-h3 and then he will win the e4 and
f5-pawns.}) 31... Rf4 32. Ka2 h4 33. Kxa3 (33. c4 h3 34. Rxh3 Bxe4 $17 {
[%csl Rf5] Black is clearly better.}) 33... h3 34. Rxh3 Bxe4 35. Rc3 Bxf5 36.
Rc7+ Ke6 37. Rd1 $6 (37. c4 {would be tenacious but White's task in this
endgame still looks very difficult.} Rf3 38. Rc6 e4 39. Rxa6 Ke5 $17) 37... Be4
38. Rd2 Bf3 {[%cal Ge5e4] A great victory by Jankovic, one of the most
important specialists of this variation.} 0-1

