1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 a6 8.
O-O-O Bd7 9. f4 b5 10. Nxc6 Bxc6 11. Bd3 b4 12. Ne2 Qb6 13. Bxf6 gxf6 14. Kb1
h5 {Black is ready to play ....Bh6 after White's f5-push. White, of course has
other options other than pushing f5 but it is not possible for White to get an
advantage over Black's central pawn island.} 15. f5 Bh6 16. Qe1 e5 $1 {Black
does not allow White to open the centre and closes the centre. Black has a
very easy plan to follow up: ...Qc5, ...Ke7, ...a5-a4-a3 to start a counter
attack against the White king. It does not seem very easy to prevent it with
White.} 17. Bc4 $6 (17. h4 $2 {White aims to improve the position by playing
Ng3 and Qe2 after fixing the h5-pawn with this typical move. But there is not
enough time for White to execute all these plans.} Ke7 18. Ng3 {0-1 (38)
Tseshkovsky,V (2485)-Damljanovic,B (2500) Vrsac 1987} Rhg8 $1 $146 19. Rh3 a5
$19 {[%cal Ga5a4,Ga4a3,Gb6c5] White pieces are located badly and are immobile.
Black is ready to weaken White king by playing ...Qc5, ...a5-a4-a3. White has
a very bad position.}) (17. Ng3 h4 18. Nf1 (18. Nh5 $6 Bg5 19. g4 hxg3 $1 20.
hxg3 Ke7 $17 {[%csl Gg5][%cal Ga6a5] 0-1 (52) Abdulov,O (2369)-Guseinov,G 
(2623) Konya 2016}) 18... Ke7 {Black has managed to bring all the pieces to
ideal squares and ready to weaken the White king by pushing ...a5-a4-a3. White
has many options but none are enough to prevent Black's initiative.} 19. Nd2 (
19. Qxh4 Rag8 $1 $17) (19. Bc4 Qc5 20. Bd3 {White has lost an important tempo.}
(20. Bd5 $2 Rac8 $19 {White cannot protect the c2-pawn.}) (20. b3 h3 21. gxh3
a5 $17 {[%cal Ga5a4] Black's position is fantastic. White has no counterplay
for Black's attack.}) 20... a5 {[%cal Ga5a4] All Black pieces are at excellent
squares and ready to launch an attack against the White king. This position is
very bad for White and in this model game for this opening Ivanchuk shows how
to treat these type of positions.} 21. Nd2 a4 22. Nc4 Bf4 23. Qf1 b3 24. cxb3
axb3 25. a3 (25. axb3 Qb4 $19 {[%csl Rb3] is hopeless for White.}) 25... Ra4
26. g3 (26. Qe2 d5 $1 27. exd5 Bxd5 28. Nd2 h3 29. Ne4 Qc6 $19 {White is
collapsed.}) 26... hxg3 27. hxg3 Rxh1 28. Qxh1 Rxc4 29. gxf4 Rc2 $1 $19 {
0-1 (36) Kryvoruchko,Y (2678)-Ivanchuk,V (2731) Tromsoe 2013}) 19... a5 20. Bc4
{1/2 (47) Vogt,L (2460)-Kiss,A (2375) Leipzig 1988} (20. Nc4 Qc5 $17 {[%cal
Ga5a4] Black is ready to play ...a4 with a clear advantage.}) 20... a4 $1 $146
21. Qe2 Qd4 $1 {[%cal Ga4a3] Black is thretening to play ...a3.} 22. Bd5 (22.
Rhe1 {[%cal Gd2f3]} a3 $19) (22. Qd3 Qxd3 23. Bxd3 Rhg8 $19 {Black's bishop
pair and pressure on the g-file is enough for a winning advantage.}) 22... Bxd5
23. exd5 {[%cal Gd2e4] White intends to play Ne4.} Bxd2 $1 {Of course Black
does not allow the knight to its ideal square, e4.} 24. Qxd2 (24. Rxd2 Qc5 $19
{[%cal Ga4a3]}) 24... Qc4 $17 {White is very passive. Black has pressure upon
the g- and c-files. The position is clearly better for Black.}) 17... Ke7 $5 {
I think 17...Qc5 is a bit stronger which we examined in Chapter 8 but in this
position, this typical move played by Kozul who has an excellent understanding
in these positions is also offering a good play for Black.} (17... Qc5 $1 18.
b3 (18. Bd5 $6 {White would like to take the control of the light-squares by
exchanging the bishops but it is impossible in this position because c2-pawn
remains defenceless.} Rc8 $1 {[%csl Rc2]} 19. c3 (19. Bxc6+ Rxc6 $1 $146 20. c3
Rg8 $19 {[%csl Rg2][%cal Gc5e3]}) 19... Bb5 $19 {White is collapsed.}) 18...
Ke7 19. Nc1 {[%cal Gc1d3] With this move White wants to bring the knight to d3.
} (19. Ng3 h4 20. Nf1 a5 $5 {[%cal Ga5a4] This interesting pawn sacrifice also
gives a large edge for Black.} ({The simple} 20... h3 $17 {is also good enough
for clear advantage.}) 21. Qxh4 Bg5 22. Qe1 Rh4 {[%csl Re4]} 23. Ng3 Be3 $17 {
All Black's pieces are very active and Black's position is clearly better.})
19... Bxc1 20. Rxc1 Rhg8 21. g3 a5 $17 {Black has occupied the dark-squares
and gives a big advantage.}) 18. b3 (18. Nc1 Rag8 $1 $146 {The same idea we
shall see in the game. It is aiming to increase the advantage by creating a
weakness on Black's kingside.} 19. g3 (19. Qe2 Bxc1 20. Kxc1 Rg4 $17 {[%csl
Re4][%cal Gh8g8] As we have seen numerous times in this pawn structure,
e4-pawn and active play of Black on the g-file is creating many problems for
White in this position, too.}) 19... h4 20. Qe2 (20. gxh4 Bxc1 21. Rxc1 Rg4 $19
{All white pawns are very weak and it is impossible to defend this position.})
20... Bxc1 21. Kxc1 hxg3 22. Qd3 Bb5 $1 23. hxg3 Bxc4 24. Qxc4 Rxh1 25. Rxh1
Rxg3 26. b3 Rc3 27. Qd5 Rc7 $17 {Black is a pawn up and has chances for the
win.}) 18... Rag8 $1 {Kozul once again demonstrates his deep understanding of
these type of positions. Instead of winning a pawn he resumes the initiative
without allowing exchanges.} (18... Bxe4 19. Nf4 Bxc2+ 20. Kxc2 Bxf4 $17 {
Of course this position is clearly better for Black but after the text Black's
advantage increases.}) 19. Ng3 (19. g3 Rg4 $19 {[%cal Gg4e4] e4-pawn is
defenceless.}) (19. Qf1 Rg4 20. Bd3 (20. Bd5 Bb5 $19) 20... Rhg8 $19 {[%csl
Rg2] Black domines the whole board.}) 19... h4 20. Nh5 Bg5 (20... Rxg2 $1 {
[%cal Gh6g5] This move would immediately finish the game.} 21. Nxf6 Kxf6 22.
Qxh4+ (22. Rxd6+ Ke7 $19) 22... Kg7 23. Rxd6 Qg1+ 24. Rd1 Qa7 25. Rd6 Rg1+ 26.
Rd1 Rxh1 27. Rxh1 f6 $19 {Black is a piece up and his position is completely
winning.}) 21. g4 (21. Qe2 Bb5 $19 {[%cal Gg8c8] Black is ready to play ...Rc8.
}) 21... Rc8 {[%csl Rh5] White's knight is completely out of play and we can
claim White is a piece down in practice.} 22. Qe2 Bb5 $1 23. Bxb5 (23. Rd5 Bxc4
24. bxc4 Rc5 $19 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gh8c8] White's c4-pawn is weak and Black is
ready to play ...Rhc8.}) 23... axb5 24. Rd5 Rc5 25. Qf2 (25. Rxc5 Qxc5 $19 {
[%cal Gh8a8,Gc5a7] White king has no defence against ...Ra8 and ...Qa7 idea.})
25... Rhc8 26. Rxc5 Rxc5 27. Qe2 Qa5 28. Rd1 Rc3 (28... Rc6 $19 {[%cal Gc6a6]
is also winning. Black is threatening to play ...Ra6.}) 29. Rd5 Qa3 {[%cal
Ga3c1] The Croatian grandmaster once again demonstrated why this variation is
called as Richter Rauzer Kozul. We can claim he has a really a deep
understanding and this win is almost perfect.} 0-1

