1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 a6 8.
O-O-O Bd7 9. f4 b5 10. Bxf6 gxf6 11. Kb1 Qb6 12. Nce2 h5 (12... Rc8 $1 {
is our main move.}) 13. g3 Rc8 14. Bg2 Na5 $5 {[%cal Ga5c4] A typical idea in
this variation. Black wants to play ...Nc4 and White is forced to push b3.
After the pawn push, c3 is weakened.} 15. b3 Nc6 {[%csl Rc3]} 16. Rhe1 (16.
Nxc6 Qxc6 17. Rhf1 (17. Nd4 Qc3 18. Qe2 Qc5 $132 {[%cal Ga6a5,Ga5a4] 1/2 (18)
Garcia Martinez,S (2430)-Zaltsman,V (2410) Havana 1985}) 17... a5 $5 18. Rf3 {
[%cal Gf3c3] White rook joins the game with this move and White threatens Rc3.}
b4 {Black prevents Rc3.} (18... Qxe4 19. f5 $44) 19. Rd3 Qc5 20. c4 bxc3 21.
Rxc3 Qb4 22. Rxc8+ Bxc8 23. Qc2 (23. Qxb4 $6 axb4 $132 {[%cal Gh5h4] Black has
good chances with the bishop pair.}) 23... Qc5 24. Qb2 Bd7 $1 {Black
sacrifices a pawn but the initiative he gets is only sufficient for equality.}
25. Qxf6 Qe3 26. Qb2 (26. Qxh8 Qxe2 27. Rxd6 Qxg2 28. Rxd7 Qxe4+ 29. Kb2 Qg2+
30. Kb1 Qh1+ 31. Kb2 Qg2+ $11 {Black has perpetual check.}) 26... h4 $1 {
With this move Black both aims to bring the rook into the game and weaken
White's king side.} 27. Rd2 (27. Qxh8 $2 Qxe2 $19 {[%cal Ge2d1,Ge2g2]}) 27...
Rh6 28. Qc3 Qxc3 29. Nxc3 hxg3 30. hxg3 Rg6 {Black has sufficient compensation
in this endgame because of the powerful bishop pair.} 31. Rd3 Rg8 32. Kc2 Ke7
33. Bf1 Bg7 34. Kd2 Rh8 35. Ke3 Rh1 36. Be2 Rh3 37. Kf3 Rh8 38. Ke3 Rh3 39. Kf2
Rh2+ 40. Ke1 Bc6 41. a3 Rh1+ 42. Kd2 Rh2 43. Ke3 {1/2 (43) Muller,H (2020)
-Kobryn,W (1877) LSS email 2012} Rh3 $11) (16. c3 Nxd4 17. Nxd4 (17. Qxd4 $2
Qxd4 18. cxd4 h4 $15 {[%csl Gd7,Gf8]}) (17. cxd4 a5 $132 {[%cal Ga5a4]}) 17...
Qc5 {[%csl Rc3]} 18. Rc1 h4 $132) (16. Rhf1 b4 17. Bf3 Ne5 $5 {Black gets a
chance for obtaining a strong counterplay with this unpexpected move.} 18. Bg2
(18. fxe5 fxe5 $132 {[%csl Rd4]}) 18... Bh6 $5 (18... Nc6 $11 {We can choose
this move if a draw is sufficient but our reason to choose this opening is
getting complicated positions with mutual chances. Because of this reason,
rather than being content with a draw, continuing the battle with 18..Bh6!?
would be a more accurate choice for Black.}) 19. Nc1 Qc5 20. Rfe1 (20. Qe2 Nc6
21. Nxc6 Bxc6 22. Nd3 (22. Qxa6 $4 Bb5 $19 {[%cal Gc5c2]}) 22... Qc3 $132 {
We see the importance of weakening the c3-square once again.}) 20... a5 {
[%cal Ga5a4] Black aims to exploit the weakness of black squares with first ...
a4 and then . ..a3 pushes.} 21. Qe2 a4 $1 22. Bf1 (22. fxe5 $2 fxe5 23. Nf3 Bb5
24. Nd3 Qc3 $19 {While black is dominating the whole board, White simply ran
out of useful moves. The position is lost for White.}) 22... Qc3 {[%cal Ga4a3]
The deadly threat is ...a3 and White has to exchange the queens. As in general,
Black has a very good game in the ending.} 23. Qd2 Qxd2 24. Rxd2 Rb8 (24... h4
$5 $132) 25. Rdd1 Ng4 26. Nf3 axb3 27. cxb3 h4 28. Rxd6 (28. Nxh4 $6 Bxf4 29.
gxf4 Rxh4 30. Rxd6 Nf2 $15) 28... Bf8 29. Rd2 hxg3 30. hxg3 Bc5 $44 31. Nd3 Be3
32. Rc2 Ke7 33. Rc4 Bb5 34. Rc7+ Kf8 35. Nc5 Be8 36. Bc4 Bf2 37. Rc1 {1/2 (38)
Jimenez Ariza,J (2365)-Manzo,A (2348) ICCF email 2014} Be3 38. Re1 Bf2 39. Rc1
Be3 $11 {The game ends in a draw by three-move repetition.}) 16... Nxd4 17.
Nxd4 Qc5 (17... a5 $5 $132 {is also interesting and gives a good counterplay
for Black.}) 18. Re3 {White both controls c3-square and prevents ...Qc3 move
and also brings his rook into the game via the third rank.} h4 {Black wants to
bring his h8-rook int game thanks to this move.} 19. Rd3 hxg3 20. hxg3 b4 21.
e5 $6 (21. Bf1 a5 22. Qg2 {[%cal Gd3d2,Gf1c4]} a4 23. R3d2 a3 24. Bc4 Be7 $132
{A very complicated middlegame with mutual chances for both sides.}) 21... fxe5
22. fxe5 Bh6 23. Qf2 (23. Qe2 $6 Qxe5 $17 {Black has a clear advantage.}) 23...
Bg7 $2 (23... Qxe5 $1 {White needs to be careful and play precise after this
strong reply.} 24. Re1 (24. Nf3 Qf6 25. Rxd6 Bg7 26. Qd4 Bb5 $15 {Black is
slightly better.}) 24... Qc5 25. Qf6 Rh7 26. Qh4 Kf8 $5 {[%cal Gf8g8]} (26...
Rh8 {[%cal Gh6g7]} 27. Qf6 Rh7 28. Qh4 $11) 27. Bc6 $1 Bxc6 28. Nxe6+ fxe6 29.
Qf6+ Kg8 30. Qxe6+ Rf7 31. Qxc8+ Kh7 32. Rdd1 Bd7 33. Qxc5 dxc5 $13) 24. exd6
O-O 25. Rh1 $2 {White misses a chance to get the upper hand with this move.} (
25. R3d2 Qe5 26. Qf4 $14 {White is slightly better.}) (25. Rf1 a5 26. Be4 Bb5
27. Nxb5 Qxb5 28. Qf4 Qc5 29. Rf2 Rcd8 30. d7 f5 31. Bb7 Rf7 32. Bc8 $16 {
The position is still complicated but it is clear that White has better
chances.}) 25... e5 {[%csl Rd4]} 26. Rh5 (26. Be4 f5 $19 {White loses a piece.}
) 26... f5 $1 27. Bb7 exd4 28. Bxc8 Qxc8 (28... Bxc8 $1 {This accurate move is
stronger than the text.} 29. Rg5 Qxd6 $19) 29. Rg5 Qc5 $2 {After this great
mistake, White gets chances to equalize.} (29... Re8 $1 30. Qxd4 Re1+ 31. Kb2
Qf8 $19 {[%cal Gg8h7,Ge1e4]}) 30. g4 Rf7 31. Qh4 Qxd6 32. gxf5 Bxf5 33. Rxd4 $4
{White commits the last mistake in this complicated game and loses the game.} (
33. Rxg7+ Rxg7 34. Rxd4 (34. Qxd4 $13) 34... Rg1+ 35. Kb2 Qc7 36. Qd8+ Qxd8 37.
Rxd8+ Kf7 38. Rd2 $11 {[%cal Ga2a3] White will play a3 and the position should
be draw.}) (33. Qxd4 Qf6 34. Qxf6 Rxf6 35. Rd4 a5 36. Rd8+ Kf7 37. Rd5 Be6 38.
Rxg7+ Kxg7 39. Rxa5 $11 {This endgame is draw.}) 33... Bg6 $1 34. Rxg6 (34.
Rxd6 Rf1+ $19) 34... Rf1+ 35. Kb2 Qxg6 36. Qd8+ Rf8 0-1

