{This pawn structure arises after f2-f4-f5 followed by fxe6. White's main
triumph in this structure is the open character of the position. Of course,
with a pawn on f7, Black's king would be safer. On the other hand, Black
enjoys a better pawn structure and control of the center. Another important
advantage is the e5-squre which is usually occupied by the knight. Given the
fact that Black has a better pawn structure, every endgame is favorable for
him. Plans for White: 1) execute the advance e4-e5 - This thematic idea is
even more effective here. Black usually answers with ...dxe5. In such
situations White should play very energetically in order to prove compensation
for the missing pawn. The main strategical risk is to completely lose the
control of the center. 2) knight sacrifices on d5 and f5 - These sacrifices
are another possibility to make use of the relatively vulnerable black king.
When Black accepts the sacrifice, White takes with the e-pawn in order to open
the e-file and to create a strong outpost on e6.3) put pressure on e6 - The
idea of putting pressure on e6 is a recurrent theme in Rauzer positions. In
this concrete case, this approach is even more relevant since there is no pawn
on f7. Of course, White's dream would be to provoke the advance e6-e5. Plans
for Black: 1) take control of the e5-square - This is probably the most
important idea in this structure. Black should try to block the e4-pawn since
the threat of e4-e5 is always an issue. As the dark-squared bishop is usually
tied to the defence of the d6-pawn, Black usually put a knight on e5. Besides
his important defensive tasks, the knight also takes part in the queenside
attack. 2) provoke simplifications and transition into an endgame - The
endgame is very favorable for Black. In every endgame, the e4-pawn is
problematic for White. Additionally, Black has the e5-square at his disposal
as well as the semi-open "c" and "g" files.}  *

