1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 a6 8.
O-O-O Bd7 9. f4 b5 10. Bxf6 gxf6 11. Nxc6 Bxc6 12. Qe1 b4 $1 13. Nd5 a5 14. f5
Bxd5 15. exd5 Bh6+ (15... e5 $5 {is interesting and my suggestion in Chapter 6.
}) 16. Kb1 e5 17. Bb5+ Ke7 18. Bc6 Rb8 {This is one of the typical positions
in this pawn structure. Black king is very safe on e7. Black's idea: ...Qb6
and then if possible, improving the position with moves like ...Be3, ...h5, ...
h4.} 19. Rd4 $5 (19. Rf1 Rg8 20. Qe4 Qb6 21. Rd3 Bg5 {[%cal Gh7h5,Gh5h4] Black
wants to play ...h5-h4.} 22. g3 (22. Rh3 a4 $1 $15 {[%cal Ga4a3] Black wants
to play ...a4-a3 and White does not have time to grab the pawn.} 23. Rxh7 $2 (
23. Bxa4 $4 Qa6 $19 {[%csl Ra4,Rf1]}) 23... a3 $17) (22. g4 Kf8 $132 {Black
has a comfortable position.}) 22... h5 23. h3 h4 $5 24. g4 (24. gxh4 $6 Bh6 $15
{[%cal Gg8g1] Black controls the g-file.}) 24... Qa7 {[%cal Ga5a4]} 25. b3 Qc5
26. Re1 Kf8 {[%cal Gf8g7]} 27. Qg2 Kg7 {The position is objectively equal but
I think it is easier to play with Black. Because, Black king is safer than its
white counterpart and White should always be alert for the Black's possible
exchange sacrifice on c6.} 28. Re4 Qb6 29. Rf3 Rgc8 30. Qf2 $2 (30. Rc4 Qa7 $11
{Position is about equal.}) 30... Rxc6 $1 {White misses this move and the
position is now winning for Black.} 31. dxc6 Qxc6 (31... d5 $1 {is stronger
than the text move and after} 32. Qxb6 Rxb6 33. Re1 e4 $19 {[%cal Gb6c6] Black
is winning.}) 32. Rc4 Qb7 33. a4 $2 d5 34. Rc5 e4 $19 {[%csl Rf3] 0-1 (51)
Istratescu,A (2641)-Jankovic,A (2543) Aix les Bains 2012}) 19... Qb6 20. Rc4 (
20. Re4 {[%cal Rh6e3]} Bg7 {[%cal Gh7h5,Gg7h6] Black wants to push ...h5 first
and then play...Bh6 . The pawn on ...h5 is important for Black. That is why I
like 15...e5 more than 15...Bh6+. Black does not close the path of h-pawn with
this move order and keeps the option for advancing ...h5.} 21. Qe2 h5 $1 22.
Rh4 Bh6 23. Rxh5 Be3 $44 {Black has very good compensation.}) 20... Be3 $1 21.
Qe2 h5 22. Re1 $6 (22. Re4 Bg1 23. Qd1 Bc5 $15 {[%csl Gc5] Black is slightly
better.}) (22. Rh4 Rbg8 23. g3 Rg5 24. Rf1 Bc5 $132) (22. Ba4 {[%cal Gc4c6]}
Bc5 $132 {[%cal Gb8g8] It is important not to allow Rc6. Now Black wants to
play for getting a good counterplay.}) 22... Bc5 (22... Bg1 $1 {[%csl Rh2]
After this strong move, Black is slightly better.} 23. h3 (23. g3 Qf2 24. Qxf2
Bxf2 25. Re2 Bc5 $17 {This endgame is clearly better for Black.}) 23... Rbg8
$15) 23. g3 {[%cal Gc4h4]} Rbg8 $1 {[%cal Gg8g5]} 24. Rh4 Rg5 {[%csl Rf5]} 25.
Rf1 (25. Qf3 Qa6 $1 $15 {[%cal Ga6c8] Black intends to play ...Qc8 to increase
pressure on the f5-pawn.}) 25... Kf8 26. Re4 $2 (26. Qc4 {would be better, but
after} Qc7 $15 {[%cal Gc7c8] Black is still slightly better.}) 26... Rg4 $1 {
Black takes the whole board under his control after this strong move.} 27. Rxg4
(27. Qc4 Bg1 $17 {[%csl Rh2] h2-pawn falls.}) 27... hxg4 {Now h8-rook entered
the game and White's h2-pawn will become a chronical weakness.} 28. Rh1 (28.
Qxg4 Rxh2 $19 {Black has a big advantage.}) 28... Bf2 {[%cal Gf2g3] Black
threatens to capture g3-pawn.} 29. Qxg4 (29. Qd3 Rh5 $19 {[%csl Rf5][%cal
Gb6e3] Black wants to play ...Qe3.}) 29... Qe3 $1 {[%cal Gf2g3]} 30. Qd1 (30.
h4 Bxg3 31. h5 Rg8 32. Qh3 Kg7 $1 33. h6+ Kh7 $19 {Black has no counterplay
and the position is hopeless for White.}) 30... Qe4 31. g4 Qc4 (31... Rh3 $1
$19 {White does not have any counterplay.}) 32. Qd2 (32. h4 Rxh4 33. Rxh4 Bxh4
$17 {In this endgame Black's e-pawn is very strong. Black has a clear
advantage.}) (32. h3 e4 $1 $17) 32... Bh4 {[%cal Gh4g5]} 33. h3 Bg5 34. Qd3 $2
{It is completely lost for White after this final mistake.} (34. Qg2 {would be
better but after} e4 $17 {Black is still clearly better and it is very
difficult to defend this position with White.}) 34... Qxg4 $1 {Probably he
missed this move.} 35. a3 Qg2 36. Rd1 Rxh3 37. Qa6 b3 38. Qc4 Rh1 39. Qd3 Bd2
40. Qxb3 Rxd1+ 41. Ka2 Bg5 $19 42. c4 Qf1 43. Qb8+ Kg7 44. Bb5 Ra1+ 45. Kb3
Qd1+ 0-1

