1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bg5 e6 {This chapter
will cover options for White other than the main move 7.Qd2 and the
interesting alternative 7.Qd3!?.} 7. Bb5 {Although this move has lost its
popularity, in the 1990s many strong grandmasters including Kamsky, Tiviakov,
and Yudasin have chosen it. Therefore it needs to be analyzed seriously. It
gives Black two options and both are good enough to solve all problems. I have
analyzed both so you can choose which suits your type of play.} (7. Bc4 Be7 8.
O-O O-O $132 {[%csl Rg5][%cal Gc8d7,Ga7a6,Ga8c8] Black has a very easy plan:
With the typical Sicilian moves ...a6, ...Bd7, ...Rc8 he wants to complete his
development. Normally the ideal place for the white bishop is e3, therefore
Black got a better version compared to the normal variation. Black has a very
comfortable position.}) (7. Be2 {White intends to complete his development by
castling short. However, this opening strategy, which is not very active, is
insufficient to create any problems for Black.} Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. Kh1 {[%cal
Gf2f4] This preparatory move allows White to play f4.} (9. Ndb5 $6 a6 10. Bxf6
Bxf6 $1 11. Nxd6 {0-1 (48) Zatonskih,A (2441)-Kovalevskaya,E (2451) Batumi 2000
} Qc7 $1 $146 {This strong novelty gives Black an edge.} 12. Nxc8 Raxc8 $15 {
[%csl Gf6][%cal Gf8d8] White managed to win the d6-pawn, but all black pieces
are very active and he has more than enough compensation.}) (9. Qd2 {This move
gives Black an opportunity to simplify and equalize with a tactical idea.} Nxe4
$5 10. Nxe4 Nxd4 11. Qxd4 Bxg5 12. Nxg5 (12. Qxd6 Be7 13. Qe5 $146 {After this
novelty, White obtains equality.} (13. Qxd8 $6 {After this dubious move, Black
is better due to the bishop pair.} Rxd8 14. Rfd1 Bd7 15. a3 Bc6 $15 {[%csl Gc6,
Ge7] 0-1 (33) Meijere,A (2180)-Knoppert,E (2385) Dieren 1997}) 13... Qd5 $5 14.
Qxd5 exd5 15. Nc3 Rd8 16. Bf3 Be6 {[%cal Ge7f6]} 17. Nb5 Bf6 18. c3 {White
wants to play Rfd1 to control the d4-square and aims to get a slight edge.} d4
{Of course Black does not allow it. This move leads to an equal endgame.} 19.
Nxd4 Bxd4 20. cxd4 Rxd4 $11 {The position is symmetrical and very close to a
draw.}) 12... Qxg5 13. Qxd6 Rd8 14. Qc7 Rd7 15. Qc3 b6 {[%cal Gc8b7] White
wants to develop his problem by playing ...Bb7.} 16. Bf3 Bb7 17. Bxb7 Rxb7 18.
Rad1 Rd8 19. Qc6 Rbb8 20. Rd7 {1-0 (44) Meijers,V (2472)-Meins,G (2421)
Baunatal 1999} Qe5 $146 {After this novelty, Black's counterplay is enough for
a draw and White will have no chances to achieve an advantage.} 21. Rfd1 Rxd7
22. Qxd7 g6 23. Qxa7 Rc8 24. Qxb6 Rxc2 25. Rb1 Qf5 26. Rf1 Qf6 27. Rb1 Qf5 $11
{Draw by repetition of moves.}) 9... d5 $5 {This move solves all of Black's
problems and equalizes easily.} 10. exd5 Nxd5 11. Nxc6 (11. Bxe7 Ncxe7 12. Nxd5
Nxd5 $11 {Black is very comfortable.}) 11... bxc6 12. Bxe7 Qxe7 13. Qd4 Rb8 14.
b3 Nb4 15. Rac1 c5 16. Qe5 Bb7 17. Rfd1 Rbd8 $11 {White's pawn structure is a
bit better but Black's active pieces will compensate for the pawn weaknesses.
The position is dynamically equal.}) 7... Bd7 {This is the most popular and
logical move.} (7... Qb6 $5 {is a very interesting alternative.} 8. Be3 Qc7 9.
g4 $5 {This is the most aggressive and interesting option for White.} (9. O-O {
After this normal-looking move, Black has no problems. He will respond ...a6
and the b5-bishop has nothing better than retreat with a loss of tempo.} Be7
10. f4 O-O 11. Be2 a6 12. Kh1 Nxd4 13. Bxd4 e5 14. Be3 b5 $132 {[%cal Gc8b7]
Black is ready to play ...Bb7 with a very comfortable position.}) 9... a6 10.
Be2 (10. g5 Nd7 11. Be2 Na5 $146 12. f4 b5 $132 {[%cal Gd7b6,Gf8e7,Gc8b7]
Black is planning to play ...Nb6, ...Bb7, ...Be7 with very good counterplay.})
10... h6 11. f3 b5 12. Nxc6 (12. a3 $6 {White prevents Black's ...b4 push with
