1/2 (29) Barendse,T (2198) -Burlage,P (2232) Wijk aan Zee 2000}) 13. Bf3 Qxd3
14. Bxc6+ Qd7 15. Rxd7 Nxd7 16. Bxa8 bxc3 17. Bc6 f6 18. Rd1 fxg5 19. fxe5 (19.
fxg5 Be7 $11 {is also equal.}) 19... Bc5 20. Rxd7 Be3+ 21. Kb1 (21. Kd1 cxb2
22. Rb7+ Kd8 23. Rxb2 Kc7 $11) 21... O-O 22. Bf3 cxb2 23. Kxb2 Rb8+ 24. Kc3 Bf4
$11 {Because of the opposite-colored bishops the endgame is equal and very
drawish.}) 10... Bxc6 11. Rhe1 Be7 {Now Black is ready to play ...b4. White
should do something about it.} 12. Bxf6 (12. a3 {White prevents Black's ...b4
idea and intends to continue with f4. But this slow move does not create any
problems for Black. Black will always exploit White's weakness on a3 push by
pushing ...b4 to open lines against the white king.} O-O $146 13. f4 h6 14. Bh4
(14. Bxf6 Bxf6 15. Qxd6 {As we have seen in many positions, White has won the
d6-pawn but in return Black gets a serious initiative.} Qb6 $1 16. e5 Rad8 17.
Qb4 a5 18. Qb3 Be7 {[%cal Gb5b4] Black wants to play ...b4.} 19. Bxb5 Rxd1+ 20.
Rxd1 Rb8 21. a4 Qe3+ 22. Kb1 Qxf4 23. g3 Qxe5 $15 {Black has the bishop pair
and a strong central pawn. His chances are preferable.}) 14... Qa5 {[%csl Ra3]
[%cal Gb5b4] Black is ready to play ...b4.} 15. Bf3 (15. e5 dxe5 16. fxe5 Nd5
17. Bxe7 Nxe7 $15 {Black has a very good position.}) 15... b4 16. axb4 Qxb4 {
[%cal Ga8b8] Black will play...Rab8 next, threatening to start an unstoppable
attack. White should react very quickly.} 17. e5 $1 Qxf4+ 18. Kb1 Qxh4 19. exf6
(19. Bxc6 Rab8 20. exf6 Bxf6 {transposes to 19.exf6}) 19... Bxf6 20. Bxc6 Rab8
{[%cal Gb8b2] Black sacrificed a piece for two pawns, but his pieces are very
active and he has enough compensation. White should play very carefully. My
conclusion is that the variation ends in a draw if both sides play accurately.}
21. Na4 d5 22. Qxa6 Qxh2 23. Re2 Qh5 24. Rf1 Rfc8 {[%cal Gc8c6,Gh5e2] Black is
threatening to play ...Rxc6.} 25. Rf3 Rc7 26. Ka2 Qg4 27. c3 Rd8 {[%cal Gd8d6]
Black would like to play ...Rd6 and White has no better alternative than allow
a draw by repetition.} 28. Bb5 Rcc8 {[%cal Gc8a8]} 29. Bc6 Rc7 30. Bb5 Rcc8 $11
{Draw by repetition of moves.}) 12... Bxf6 $1 {This is the correct way to play
this position. Black sacrifices the d6-pawn for activity.} (12... gxf6 $6 {
is dubious and White has slight advantage after} 13. Bh5 $14 {1-0 (45) Tolnai,
T (2500)-Grosar,A (2480) Bad Woerishofen 1993}) 13. Qxd6 Qxd6 14. Rxd6 Rc8 15.
f4 g5 $1 {As we have seen many times, this typical idea leaves White's pawns
weak and secures counterplay on the g-file.} 16. g3 (16. Nd5 Be7 17. Nxe7 Kxe7
18. e5 gxf4 19. Rd4 Rhg8 $132 {Black is very comfortable and White should be
careful to keep the position equal.}) 16... gxf4 17. gxf4 {1/2 (61) Swiercz,D 
(2478) -Vidit,S (2356) Vung Tau 2008} Rg8 $146 {[%cal Gg8g2] After this
natural novelty, Black gets the g-file under his control and achieves enough
play in return for the pawn.} 18. Bf3 Bxc3 19. bxc3 Ke7 20. Rd2 Rg6 $44 {
[%csl Rc3][%cal Gg6h6,Gh6h4] Black's idea is to exert pressure against the
white pawns by playing ...Rh6-h4. White's pawn formation is very weak and
Black's pieces are well-located. Despite being a pawn down Black has a very
comfortable position.} *

