{[%evp 0,40,29,28,47,53,95,58,65,29,44,50,52,41,57,43,60,36,33,24,23,2,33,-5,
44,10,55,20,62,52,40,63,52,74,48,16,17,3,55,63,62,28,-1]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3.
d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 a6 8. O-O-O Bd7 9. f3 {This
one and the next chapter will cover 9.f3, which is very typical in the
Sicilian. White's main idea is to start a kingside attack with h4-g4. This
chapter will cover the most popular move for Black, 9...Be7 and the following
chapter will cover the trending 9...Nxd4. According to my analyses, both are
playable and give Black good chances. In the computer era, having different
options in our openings and surprising our opponent is important, therefore
I'm presenting both continuations.} Be7 {The most popular move and the old
main line.} 10. h4 {White starts to advance his kingside pawns without waiting
for Black to castle short. This move can have some upside for White compared
to 10.g4 because of the protection it provides to the bishop on g5.} (10. g4 h5
{With this typical move Black spoils White's pawn structure without allowing
White to start a kingside attack.} 11. gxh5 (11. Be2 $2 {is a mistake because
after} hxg4 12. fxg4 b5 $146 {[%cal Gb5b4] White's pawn formation is spoiled
and e4 is very weak. Black already threatens to push ...b4.} 13. a3 Rh3 14.
Rhf1 (14. Bf1 Rxc3 $1 {This typical Sicilian exchange sac helps Black to win
the e4-pawn and force a good endgame.} 15. Qxc3 Nxe4 16. Bxe7 Nxc3 17. Bxd8
Nxd1 18. Bb6 Nxb2 19. Kxb2 Rb8 20. Bc7 Rb7 21. Nxe6 Bxe6 22. Bxd6 Rd7 23. Bc5
Bxg4 $15 {Black is a pawn up and he has a slightly better position.}) 14... Qa5
15. Nb3 Qxc3 $3 {This fascinating idea gives black an edge.} 16. Qxc3 (16. bxc3
$2 {is a blunder as after} Nxe4 $19 {Black is winning.}) 16... Rxc3 17. bxc3
Nxe4 18. Bxe7 Kxe7 19. Bf3 (19. Rd3 $6 Rh8 $17 {All white pawns are weak and
Black has a big edge in this endgame.}) 19... Nxc3 20. Rd3 Na4 $15 {Black has
won two pawns. Despite being an exchange down the position is slightly better
for him.}) 11... Nxh5 12. Bxe7 (12. Be3 Ng3 13. Rg1 Nxf1 14. Rdxf1 Bf6 15. Nxc6
Bxc6 16. Bd4 Be5 {With this move Black forces White to push f4 and weaken his
central pawns.} 17. f4 Bxd4 18. Qxd4 Qf6 $1 19. Qxd6 Rd8 20. Qc7 (20. Qc5 Rxh2
21. Rf2 Rxf2 22. Qxf2 Qd4 $132 {Black has a very comfortable position. White
should be careful.}) 20... Rd7 21. Qb8+ Rd8 {1/2 (21) Sadowski,M (2143)-Wosch,
A (2269) LSS email 2009} 22. Qc7 Rd7 $11 {Draw by repetition of moves.}) 12...
Qxe7 {Black controls the dark-squares after exchanging the dark-squared
bishops. In return for Black's weakness on d6, White has a weak pawn on h2. We
can conclude that both sides have equal chances.} 13. Rg1 (13. Nxc6 $146 Bxc6
14. Qxd6 $6 {is dubious because after} Qxd6 15. Rxd6 Ng3 16. Rg1 Nxf1 17. Rxf1
Rxh2 $15 {Black has a slightly better position.}) (13. Nde2 g5 $5 {With this
move Black wants to increase his superiority over the dark squares by
sacrificing the d6-pawn.} 14. Rg1 (14. Qxd6 Qxd6 15. Rxd6 Ne5 16. Bg2 Ke7 17.
Rd2 {0-1 (74) Nowicki,B (2262)-Korneev,O (2563) Fano 2017} b5 $44 {Black has
very good compensation.}) 14... Ne5 {[%csl Rf3]} 15. Qe3 Nc4 $1 $146 {is a
