1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 a6 8.
O-O-O Bd7 9. f4 b5 10. a3 $5 {As can be seen clearly, White prevents his
knight from being kicked out from c3 with the b4-push. From now on his most
dangerous plan is Nf3 followed by the e5-push. Of course, a3 has its own
drawbacks. White's king's front is weakened and gives Black chances to obtain
counterplay by ...b4.} Be7 {Black completes his development with this natural
move. After short castling, he will be ready for his counterplay. White has
numerous options in this position.} ({The direct} 10... b4 $2 {is a big
mistake.} 11. axb4 Nxb4 12. e5 $1 h6 (12... dxe5 13. fxe5 h6 14. Bh4 g5 15.
exf6 gxh4 {1-0 (19) Krauss,G-Aykent,S USA corr 1991} 16. Bc4 $1 $18 {[%csl Re8]
Black's king is very weak and White is completely winning.}) 13. Bxf6 gxf6 14.
Ne4 $16 {White has a clear advantage.}) 11. Nf3 {[%cal Ge4e5] White threatens
