1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 a6 8.
O-O-O Bd7 9. f4 b5 10. Bxf6 gxf6 11. f5 {White aims to pressure Black's center
without losing time with preparatory moves like Kb1. There are two good
continuations in this position. The first one is 11...Qb6 that we shall
examine in this Chapter and the other is very interesting 11...Nxd4 which will
be covered in Chapter 10. Both continuations give Black decent chances,
therefore, it is up to the reader to choose the variation according to his own
taste. However, in modern chess where computer analyses are of utmost
importance, having more than one option for an opening is very useful and
recommendable.} Qb6 12. Nxc6 (12. Nce2 $6 {White wants to keep the knight in
the center on d4 but after this dubious move Black forces White to exchange
queens and leads to a slightly better endgame.} Qa5 $1 13. Qxa5 (13. Kb1 Qxd2
14. Rxd2 Bh6 15. Rd3 Ne5 16. Rh3 Bg5 17. fxe6 fxe6 18. Nf3 {0-1 (54) Sarosi,Z 
(2395)-Siklosi,Z (2315) Budapest 1996} Ke7 $1 $17 {Black is much better in
this endgame.}) 13... Nxa5 14. Kb1 {[%cal Ge2f4]} Bh6 {Black both develops the
bishop and prevents White's Nf4 idea.} 15. g3 Nc4 {[%cal Gc4d2]} 16. Nb3 Ke7
17. Nf4 Rhg8 $15 {Black has better prospects.}) (12. fxe6 fxe6 13. Nxc6 Bxc6 {
transposes to the main line.}) 12... Bxc6 13. fxe6 {The most popular move. The
main idea for White is to leave the Black central pawns weak and start
attacking by 14.Qf4.} (13. Kb1 {transposes to the Chapter 1.}) (13. Qe1 b4 $1
$146 14. Nd5 Bxd5 15. exd5 Bh6+ 16. Kb1 e5 $132 {[%cal Ge8e7,Ga6a5,Ga5a4,Gb6c5]
We have examined this pawn structure under the title Structure 6 and Chapter 6
and we now know that Black does not have any problems in this type of
positions.}) (13. Bd3 {is a very logical developing move.} b4 14. Ne2 h5 {
[%cal Gf8h6] Now Black aims to play ...Bh6.} 15. fxe6 (15. Kb1 Bh6 16. Qe1 e5 {
transposes to Chapter 8.}) 15... fxe6 16. Kb1 Bh6 17. Qe1 Qc5 18. Rf1 (18. g3 {
[%cal Ge2f4] White intends to play Nf4 after this move but it does not give an
edge for White.} a5 19. Nf4 {0-1 (35) Collins,S (2448)-Vovk,A (2637) Escaldes
