1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 a6 8.
O-O-O Bd7 9. f4 b5 10. Bxf6 gxf6 11. Kb1 Qb6 12. Nf3 {We have seen the same
idea with the 12.Nb3 move. White does not allow piece exchanges. The knight on
f3 is much better than on b3.} (12. Nf5 $5 {Despite being a typical Sicilian
sacrifice, the position has been seldomly tried. Nevertheless, we shall
prepare it well, taking it seriously. It is not pleasant to see such surprises
over the board. The idea of this sacrifice is, of course, to put the knight on
the d5-square and to utilize the e-file after capturing exf5. After this, if
there is time, then White wants to attack the Black king by pushing g4-h4-g5.}
exf5 13. Nd5 Qd8 $1 14. exf5 Bg7 $1 {[%cal Ge8g8] The right way to develop the
bishop. Now Black wants to castle short and when white gives a check on the
e-file the king will go the f8.} (14... Be7 $2 {would be a big mistake. After}
15. g4 $16 {[%cal Gf1g2,Gh1e1] White has an easy play. By completing his
development with Bg2 and Rhe1, White will increase the pressure on the Black
king. Black is very passive and has no idea how to fix the position. The
position is clearly better for White.}) 15. Re1+ {This is the most logical and
best move for White. White cannot allow Black to castle.} (15. Qe3+ $6 $146 {
[%cal Gd5b6] After black king runs away to f8, White wants to play Nb6 but the
plan is dubious and if Black plays accurately, he gets a big edge.} Kf8 16. Nb6
Rb8 $1 17. Nxd7+ Qxd7 18. Qa3 Qc7 {White has many options but none can prevent
Black from getting a big edge.} 19. Qxd6+ (19. Qxa6 Bh6 20. g3 Kg7 $19) (19.
Rxd6 b4 20. Qd3 Ke7 21. Rd5 Rhd8 $19) 19... Qxd6 20. Rxd6 Rc8 {[%cal Gf8e7]}
21. Rd7 Bh6 22. g3 Kg7 $17 {[%cal Gh8d8] Black is clearly better in this
endgame and he has a very good chance to convert his advantage.}) (15. Bd3 $6 {
is also dubious and gives a very big advantage for Black.} O-O 16. h4 Qa5 17.
Qf2 (17. b4 Qd8 $19 {[%cal Ga6a5] Black is ready to push ...a5.}) (17. c3 b4 $1
18. Nxb4 Nxb4 19. cxb4 Qb6 $19 {[%cal Gf8b8,Ga6a5] Black wants to play ...Rfb8
and ...a5. It is winning for Black.}) 17... Nb4 {After exchanging White's
strong knight on d5, the position will be winning for Black.} 18. Nxb4 Qxb4 19.
h5 h6 20. Rh4 Kh7 21. Rg4 Qc5 22. Qg3 Rg8 {[%csl Rf5]} 23. Qf3 Bxf5 24. Bxf5+
Qxf5 $19 {0-1 (31) Hj,A (2072)-Ashwin,J (2431) Kuala Lumpur 2010}) 15... Kf8
16. Bd3 {[%cal Gg2g4] White is ready to play g4.} (16. g4 $146 h5 $1 {is very
strong move.} 17. Bg2 {[%cal Gd5b6] White now threatens to play Nb6.} (17. Bd3
$2 hxg4 18. Rhg1 Nd4 {[%cal Gd4f3]} 19. Be4 Nf3 20. Bxf3 gxf3 $19 {[%csl Rf5]
White will lose the f5-pawn and Black's position is winning.}) 17... Rc8 $1 (
17... hxg4 $6 18. Nb6 $1 $36) 18. h3 hxg4 19. hxg4 (19. Nb6 Qxb6 20. Qxd6+ Kg8
21. Qxd7 Rc7 22. Re8+ Bf8 23. Qd6 Re7 24. Rxe7 Bxe7 25. Qxc6 Qxc6 26. Bxc6 gxh3
$17 {Black is clearly better and he has very good winning chances.}) 19... Rxh1
20. Bxh1 (20. Rxh1 Ne7 $1 {We neutralize the entire White initiative by
removing his most powerful piece, the d5-knight.} 21. Nxe7 Qxe7 22. Re1 Qd8 23.
